"Mosnaim A.","Estimating CO2 abatement and sequestration potentials for Chile",2001,"Energy Policy","29","8",,"631","640",,,10.1016/S0301-4215(00)00160-9,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035372170&partnerID=40&md5=3d99f5e98ab5c42c6f8de380a1c6ce59","Department of Industrial and Systems Engineering, Pontifical Catholic University of Chile, Chile; Reyes Lavalle 3135 Dpt. 22. Las Condes, Santiago, Chile","Mosnaim, A., Department of Industrial and Systems Engineering, Pontifical Catholic University of Chile, Chile, Reyes Lavalle 3135 Dpt. 22. Las Condes, Santiago, Chile","The need for the Chilean government to adopt a position vis-à-vis negotiations at the Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change prompts a preliminary analysis in this paper of the results of reductions of greenhouse gases (GHG) and their costs for Chile. Basically, two sectors offer possibilities to contribute to the control of CO2 emissions. In the energy sector, CO2 emissions can be abated by either adopting more efficient technologies or switching fuels. In the non-energy sector, CO2 emissions can be sequestered from the atmosphere by afforestation, reforestation and forest management. This work represent the first effort in Chile to estimate the costs of CO2 abatement and sequestration for Chile using a bottom-up approach for the year 2010, which in a global warming context is a short/medium term scenario. In the energy sector, the end and intermediate uses of energy are considered for the transportation, manufacturing and electricity sectors. In the non-energy sector, sequestration costs incurred in forestation on marginal land available in each administrative region of Chile are estimated. Our preliminary results indicate that Chile has a large potential to become a net remover of GHG emissions, with a 176% of CO2 equivalent reduction attainable by 2010 under the upper-bound scenario. A 7% CO2 abatement can be achieved at apparently no cost to society with increased efficiency in the use of energy, and a 114% abatement can be achieved at moderate costs, i.e., less than 11 US$/ton CO2 eq. The major reduction is obtainable through CO2 sequestration by forests. © 2001 Published by Elsevier Science Ltd.","Abatement and sequestration; GHG","Carbon dioxide; Electricity; Fuels; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Industrial emissions; Reforestation; Transportation; Abatement; Energy sectors; Energy policy; carbon emission; carbon sequestration; climate change; emission control; Chile",,,,,,"(1997) Balance Nacional De Energia (1977-1996), , Comisión Nacional de la Energia, Santiago, Chile; (1999) Technology Data Bank, , IIASA, CO2DB. IIASA; (1999) Finalización Del Inventario De Gases Invernadero Y Análisis De Opciones De Mitigación, Sector No Energia, , INIA, Instituto de Investigación Agropecuaria, Santiago, Chile; (1995) IPCC Guidelines for National Greenhouse Gas Inventories, 3. , IPCC, IPCC WGI Technical Support Unit, Bracknell, UK; Climate change 1995 (1996) Economic and Social Dimensions of Climate Change. Contribution of Working Group III to the Second Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , IPCC, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; (1996) Inventory of Technologies, Methods, and Practices for Reducing Emissions of Greenhouse Gases, , IPCC, Unpublished manuscript; Climate change 1995 (1996) The Science of Climate Change. Contribution of Working Group I to the Second Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , IPCC, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Montero, J.P., Cifuentes, L., Soto, F., (1999) Cambio Climático, Permisos Transables Y Participación Voluntaria: Implicancias Para Chile, , Santiago, Chile unpublished manuscript; Mosnaim, A., Estimación de los Costos de Abatimiento de GEI para Chile (1999) Ingenieria Industrial, , Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Moulton, R.J., Richard, K.R., (1990) Costs of Sequestering Carbon Through Tree Planting in the US, , US Department of Agriculture, Forest Service, USA; (1991) Policy Implications of Greenhouse Warming, , National Academy of Science (NAS), NAE and IOM, National Academy Press. Washington, DC, USA; Noe, D., (1999) Costos Y Potenciales De Captura De Carbono Para El Sector Forestal En Chile, , Ingenieria Industrial. Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Inventario de Emisiones de Gas de Efecto Invernadero (1994) Programa Investigación En Energía, , PRIEN, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; (1996) Uso Eficiente De La Electricidad En Chile (1994-2020), , PRIEN Universidad de Chile, IIEC y NRDC, PRIEN, Santiago, Chile; Mitigación de Gases de Efecto Invernadero, 1994-2020 (1999) Programa Investigación En Energia, , PRIEN, Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Estudio de Seguimiento del Plan Piloto de Utilización de Combustible Gaseosos en Buses de la Región Metropolitana (1999) Evaluación Económica, 2. , Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Escuela de Ingenieria, unpublished manuscript; (1994) UNEP Greenhouse Gas Abatement Costing Studies, (PART 1). , UNEP Collaborating Centre on Energy and Enviorment, riso Phase 2, main report national laboratory, Dinamarca; (1998) UNEP the Economics of Greenhouse Gas Limitation Technical Guidelines, , UNEP Collaborating Centre on Energy and Environment, riso national laboratory, Riso National Laboratory, Febrero; Ybema, J.R., Prospects for energy technologies in the Netherlands (1995) Technology Characterization and Technology Results, 2. , ECN, Petten","Mosnaim, A.; Dpt. of Indus. System Engineering, Pontifical Catholic Univ. of Chile, 3135 Dpt. 22 Reyes Lavalle, Las Condes, Santiago, Chile; email: mosnaim@rdc.cl",,,,,,,,03014215,,ENPYA,,"English","Energy Policy",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-0035372170
